reference.unstructured: The issues presented in this chapter have been the object of interest of Polish historiography, although they have not been collected in any separate monographic work. A number of interesting problems still demand individual analysis. Among the works concerned with the subject the following should be mentioned: B. Grochulska, Ksiestwo Warszawskie (Warsaw, 1966); idem, ‘Lewica wobec Napoleona w swietle “Korrespondencji w materiach obraz kraju i narodu rozjasniajacych” ’, in Francja — Polska XVIII–XIX w. (Warsaw, 1983); H. Grynwaser, ‘Kodeks Napoleona w Polsce’, in idem, Pisma (Wroclaw, 1951), vol. 1; M. Handelsman, Rozwój narodowosci nowoczesnej (Warsaw, 1973); M. Janowski, Polska mysl liberalna do 1918 r. (Cracow, 1998). T. Kizwalter, Kryzys Oswiecenia a poczatki konserwatyzmu polskiego (Warsaw, 1987); idem, O nowoczesnosci narodu. Przypadek polski (Warsaw, 1999); B. Lesnodorski, ‘Jakobini wobec zagadnień wzrostu i wspólnoty politycznej w Ksiestwie Warszawskim’, in idem, Studia historyczne (Warsaw, 1965). M. Mycielski, Kajetan Kozmian. Ewolucja konserwatysty (forthcoming); T. Walachowicz, Kosciól w prawodawstwie Ksiestwa Warszawskiego (Lublin, 1983). 2 The Duchy of Warsaw (with 4.3 million inhabitants) was represented by about 85,000 soldiers; the rest were volunteers from the Russian partition.
H. Kollataj, Uwagi nad terazniejszym polozeniem tej czesci ziemi polskiej, ktora od pokoju tylz·yckiego zaczeto zwać Ksiestwem Warszawskim (Leipzig, 1808), pp. 148–9.

One of the authors who clearly expressed and emphasised such a view was Stanislaw Staszic, one of the leading publicists of the Polish Enlightenment. He was a member of the State Council during the Duchy of Warsaw. In a brochure published before the meeting of the Sejm, calling on the citizens of the Duchy to take special care of the public interest, he recalled the state’s defeat under the partitions and the then common dream of owning at least a tiny piece of an independent state. S. Staszic, Do sejmu: co sie z nami stanie? (Warsaw, 1809), pp. 21–4.
B. Grochulska, ‘Kraków w systemie warszawsko-francuskim’, in Kraków w czasach Ksiestwa Warszawskiego (Cracow, 1989), p. 13.

‘On aime les corps délibérants, les administrations collectives, on interprête les ordres, on ne les exécute jamais sans remonstrances et souvent on ne les exécute pas du tout ….’ E. Vincent’s report, Warsaw, 2 October 1807, in M. Handelsman (ed.), Instructions et dépêches des residents de France à Varsovie 1807–1813 (Cracow, 1914), vol. 1, p. 32.
‘Note transmise par le maréchal Davout’, 9 October 1807, in C. de Mazade (ed.), Correspondance du maréchal Davout 1801–1815 (Paris, 1885), vol. 2, pp. 79–80.
The text of the satire is published in J. Czubaty, ‘Kraj pod rzadami zlodziei, masonów i rozpusty. Konserwatywna swiadomosć okresu przelomu 1807–1814’, Regiony, no. 1–3 (1998).

In this respect, the opinion of the Senate’s Secretary, Julian Ursyn Niemcewicz, is characteristic: the Pole tolerates difficult allies, knowing that ‘the ones that press him were the beginning of his existence, and hold our sweetest hopes in their hand.’ J. U. Niemcewicz, Pamietnik o czasach Ksiestwa Warszawskiego 1807–1809 (Warsaw, 1902), p. 82.
See A. Zahorski, Spór o Napoleona we Francji i w Polsce (Warsaw, 1974); A. Nieuwaz· ny, My z Napoleonem (Wroclaw, 1999).
